benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/customFields/search - Search custom fields by type, name and optional value

covered: Valid Request: Numerous scenarios cover successful retrieval with various query parameters (objectType, fieldName, fieldValue) and combinations (TC02–TC07, TC12, TC37).
Empty Response / State variation: Tests for empty database (TC28) and empty/matching results (TC11) are present.
Pagination: Scenario explicitly tests pagination via limit and offset (TC07), and large datasets/limits (TC21, TC31) walk through pagination-related behavior.
Authentication/Authorization: Tests cover missing auth (TC17) and expected 200 with valid auth across scenarios.
Audit logging: Scenarios cover FULL/MINIMAL/NONE audit flags (TC08–TC10, TC16), including integration/degradation cases (TC32, TC33).
Input validation and security: Tests for invalid objectType (TC13), invalid offset/limit (TC14–TC15), invalid audit value (TC16), SQL injection (TC19), and XSS (TC20).
Performance considerations: Basic performance checks with normal and peak loads (TC30_TC31) and heavy load scenarios (TC24, TC21).
Regression/integration: Regression tests for fieldName filtering (TC25) and FULL audit completeness (TC26), as well as integration with audit log service (TC32).
Backward compatibility: Legacy behavior with only objectType parameter (TC27).
gaps: Pagination: While TC07 covers offset/limit, there isn’t a dedicated explicit test for paginated responses across large data sets with varying page sizes beyond initial limit/offset checks (e.g., verifying consistent ordering across pages, and boundary conditions at end of data).
Caching Behavior: No tests verify caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or client-side cache effects.
Rate Limiting: No explicit tests for rate limiting or throttling when bursts of requests occur (beyond concurrent request scenario TC23).
Authorization Nuances: While TC17 covers missing auth, deeper coverage of 403 vs 401 distinctions or token refresh handling isn’t present.

More explicit error surface coverage: Some error-body expectations are described generally (e.g., “error message indicating invalid input”), but detailed structured error payload checks (codes, fields, and details) are limited.

Specific schema/contract validations: While many tests assert array of CustomField objects and schema conformance, there isn’t a dedicated test for ensuring exact schema compliance across all fields in all parameter combinations (beyond general assertions).
recommendations: Add explicit pagination boundary tests across larger datasets (e.g., page size variations, end-of-data behavior, and consistent ordering).
Introduce tests for caching headers and ETag/Cache-Control semantics to satisfy caching guidelines.
Add rate-limiting/throttling scenarios to ensure system handles bursts or excessive requests gracefully.
Expand authorization edge cases (403 vs 401, token expiration, role-based access) to strengthen authentication coverage.
Enhance error payload validation with exact error codes and structured details for different invalid inputs (objectType, offset, limit, audit, etc.).
Increase coverage for data-driven integration tests with dependent services under varying availability (mock degradations beyond TC33), and verify recovery behavior (TC36) in broader contexts.
Include explicit test for partial input (TC37) to ensure behavior when only a subset of allowed parameters is provided remains consistent across more parameter mixes.
